<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-graphing-tangent" original="PRECALC/modules/m49389/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Graphing Tangent</title>

  <!-- Content summary: - Show how to Graph tangent, asymptotes -->

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Draw graphs of trigonometric functions in degrees and radians</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from PRECALC fs-id1321556: Analyzing the Graph of y = tan x -->
  
  <p>We will begin with the graph of the <term>tangent</term> function, plotting points as we did for the sine and cosine functions. Recall that</p>
  
  <p>
      <me>tanx=\frac{sinx}{cosx}</me>
    </p>
  
  <p>The <term>period</term> of the tangent function is <m>π</m> because the graph repeats itself on intervals of <m>kπ</m> where <m>k</m> is a constant. If we graph the tangent function on <m>-\frac{π}{2}</m> to <m>\frac{π}{2},</m> we can see the behavior of the graph on one complete cycle. If we look at any larger interval, we will see that the characteristics of the graph repeat.</p>
  
  <p>We can determine whether tangent is an odd or even function by using the definition of tangent.</p>
  
  <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>tan(−x)=\frac{sin(−x)}{cos(−x)} &amp; \text{ Definition of tangent }.</mrow>
        <mrow>=\frac{-sinx}{cosx} &amp; \text{ Sine is an odd function, cosine is even }.</mrow>
        <mrow>=-\frac{sinx}{cosx} &amp; \text{ The quotient of an odd and an even function is odd }.</mrow>
        <mrow>=-tanx &amp; \text{ Definition of tangent }.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  
  <p>Therefore, tangent is an odd function. We can further analyze the graphical behavior of the tangent function by looking at values for some of the special angles, as listed in <xref ref="PRECALC-DAXSwI22Sr" />.</p>
  
  <table xml:id="PRECALC-DAXSwI22Sr" original="PRECALC/modules/m49389/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>
            <em>
              <m>x</m>
            </em>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>-\frac{π}{2}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>-\frac{π}{3}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>-\frac{π}{4}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>-\frac{π}{6}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>0</cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\frac{π}{6}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\frac{π}{4}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\frac{π}{3}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\frac{π}{2}</m>
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            <em>
              <m>tan(x)</m>
            </em>
          </cell>
          <cell>undefined</cell>
          <cell>
            <m>-\sqrt{3}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>–1</cell>
          <cell>
            <m>-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>0</cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>1</cell>
          <cell>
            <m>\sqrt{3}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell>undefined</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  
  <p>These points will help us draw our graph, but we need to determine how the graph behaves where it is undefined. If we look more closely at values when <m>\frac{π}{3} &lt; x &lt; \frac{π}{2},</m> we can use a table to look for a trend. Because <m>\frac{π}{3}≈1.05</m> and <m>\frac{π}{2}≈1.57,</m> we will evaluate <m>x</m> at radian measures <m>1.05 &lt; x &lt; 1.57</m> as shown in <xref ref="PRECALC-YXw52dski8" />.</p>
  
  <table xml:id="PRECALC-YXw52dski8" original="PRECALC/modules/m49389/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>
            <em>
              <m>x</m>
            </em>
          </cell>
          <cell>1.3</cell>
          <cell>1.5</cell>
          <cell>1.55</cell>
          <cell>1.56</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            <em>
              <m>tanx</m>
            </em>
          </cell>
          <cell>3.6</cell>
          <cell>14.1</cell>
          <cell>48.1</cell>
          <cell>92.6</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  
  <p>As <m>x</m> approaches <m>\frac{π}{2},</m> the outputs of the function get larger and larger. Because <m>y=tanx</m> is an odd function, we see the corresponding table of negative values in <xref ref="PRECALC-5ld3G19COF" />.</p>
  
  <table xml:id="PRECALC-5ld3G19COF" original="PRECALC/modules/m49389/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>
            <em>
              <m>x</m>
            </em>
          </cell>
          <cell>−1.3</cell>
          <cell>−1.5</cell>
          <cell>−1.55</cell>
          <cell>−1.56</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>
            <em>
              <m>tanx</m>
            </em>
          </cell>
          <cell>−3.6</cell>
          <cell>−14.1</cell>
          <cell>−48.1</cell>
          <cell>−92.6</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  
  <p>We can see that, as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\frac{π}{2},</m> the outputs get smaller and smaller. Remember that there are some values of <m>x</m> for which <m>cosx=0.</m> For example, <m>cos(\frac{π}{2})=0</m> and <m>cos(\frac{3π}{2})=0.</m> At these values, the <term>tangent function</term> is undefined, so the graph of <m>y=tanx</m> has discontinuities at <m>x=\frac{π}{2}\text{ and }\frac{3π}{2}.</m> At these values, the graph of the tangent has vertical asymptotes. <xref ref="PRECALC-6uNuLqj04L" /> represents the graph of <m>y=tanx.</m> The tangent is positive from 0 to <m>\frac{π}{2}</m> and from <m>π</m> to <m>\frac{3π}{2},</m> corresponding to quadrants I and III of the unit circle.</p>
  
  <figure xml:id="PRECALC-6uNuLqj04L" original="PRECALC/modules/m49389/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <caption>Graph of the tangent function</caption>
      <image source="PRECALC/CNX_Precalc_Figure_06_02_001.jpg" width="80%" />
    </figure>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-graphing-tangent" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-college-algebra-bundle/tree/e10e6b91143fe884c7c60dc0ad82ef23e1be0aa5/modules/m49389/index.cnxml">Analyzing the Graph of y = tan x</url>" in Open STAX Precalculus 2e, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->
</section>
